# Solution: rust_api_microservice_expert_008_architectural_understanding_expert_01

## Key Files Identified

### Caching Modules
- `/app/project/src/module_9.txt` - Core response cache layer with `ResponseCache::purge_namespace()` invalidation method
- `/app/project/src/module_44.txt` - Ledger Entry listing with Redis response-level caching (read handler)
- `/app/project/src/module_72.txt` - Pagination + Response Caching facade with `purge()` method

### Read Handler Modules (GET Operations)
- `/app/project/src/module_26.txt` - Ledger Entry Query Endpoint using actix-web with `#[get("/api/v1/ledger/entries")]` route
- `/app/project/src/module_52.txt` - High-frequency paginated read-model with Redis response-caching via `LedgerEntryService`
- `/app/project/src/module_44.txt` - Ledger Entry listing via `list_ledger_entries_handler` with Axum

### Write Handler Modules (INSERT/UPDATE Operations)
- `/app/project/src/module_38.txt` - Contains `insert()` method that writes to DB without cache invalidation
- `/app/project/src/module_67.txt` - `LedgerEntryService::create_entry()` with partial cache invalidation (only individual entry cache, not paginated response cache)

### Configuration
- `/app/project/src/config.txt` - Contains `ResponseCacheConfig` with `duration` (default 5 minutes TTL) and `enabled` flag

## Code Evidence

### Core Caching Module with Invalidation Support (module_9.txt)
```rust
// File: /app/project/src/module_9.txt
// Lines: 185-196

    /// Remove all keys for a given tenant namespace.  Useful when a ledger
    /// mutation happens and cached projections must be invalidated.
    #[instrument(skip(self))]
    pub async fn purge_namespace(&self, namespace: &str) -> Result<u64, CacheError> {
        let pattern = format!("{}:{}:*", self.prefix, namespace);
        let mut conn = self.conn.write().await;
        // NOTE: SCAN could be more graceful for prod, kept simple here.
        let keys: Vec<String> = conn.keys(pattern).await?;
        let deleted: u64 = conn.del(keys).await?;
        debug!("purged {} stale cache entries under '{}'", deleted, namespace);
        Ok(deleted)
    }
```

### Read Handler with Caching (module_44.txt)
```rust
// File: /app/project/src/module_44.txt
// Lines: 355-408

    #[instrument(skip(self))]
    pub async fn list(
        &self,
        tenant: Uuid,
        query: ListQuery,
    ) -> Result<Paginated<LedgerEntryDto>, ServiceError> {
        // 1. Try cache (30ms timeout to avoid head-of-line blocking)
        let key = Self::cache_key(tenant, &query);
        if let Ok(Some(raw)) = self.try_fetch_cache(&key).await {
            debug!(%tenant, %key, "Cache hit");
            return serde_json::from_slice::<Paginated<LedgerEntryDto>>(&raw)
                .map_err(ServiceError::CacheSerialization);
        }

        // 2. Query repository
        debug!(%tenant, "Cache miss – querying DB");
        let (entries, total) = self.repo.list(tenant, &query).await?;
        // ... builds paginated response ...

        // 3. Backfill cache (best-effort)
        let _ = self.persist_cache(&key, &payload).await;

        Ok(payload)
    }

    async fn persist_cache<T: Serialize>(&self, key: &str, value: &T) -> Result<(), ServiceError> {
        let mut conn: RedisConn = self.redis.get().await?;
        let data = serde_json::to_vec(value)?;
        let _: () = conn
            .set_ex(key, data, 60) // 60 seconds TTL
            .await
            .map_err(ServiceError::Cache)?;
        Ok(())
    }
```

### Write Handler WITHOUT Cache Invalidation (module_38.txt)
```rust
// File: /app/project/src/module_38.txt
// Lines: 282-306

/// An *idempotent* command that inserts a ledger entry inside its own
/// transaction.  Exposed as a convenience; not part of the trait.
///
/// Demonstrates how we keep read & write paths separated (`CQRS` style).
impl LedgerEntryPgRepository {
    #[instrument(skip_all, name = "repo.ledger.insert")]
    pub async fn insert(&self, entry: &LedgerEntry) -> Result<(), PaginationError> {
        let mut tx = self.pool.begin().await?;

        sqlx::query(
            r#"
            INSERT INTO ledger_entries
            (id, account_id, amount, currency, description, created_at)
            VALUES ($1, $2, $3, $4, $5, $6)
            ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING
            "#,
        )
        .bind(entry.id)
        .bind(entry.account_id)
        .bind(entry.amount)
        .bind(&entry.currency)
        .bind(&entry.description)
        .bind(entry.created_at)
        .execute(&mut tx)
        .await?;

        tx.commit().await?;
        Ok(())
        // NOTE: NO CACHE INVALIDATION IS PERFORMED HERE
    }
}
```

### Read Handler with Response Caching (module_26.txt)
```rust
// File: /app/project/src/module_26.txt
// Lines: 317-386

#[get("/api/v1/ledger/entries")]
#[instrument(skip(dto, state, auth), fields(tenant = %auth.tenant_id))]
pub async fn get_ledger_entries(
    auth: AuthContext,
    Query(dto): Query<LedgerEntryQueryDto>,
    state: Data<AppState>,
) -> Result<Json<Paginated<LedgerEntry>>, ApiError> {
    // ... validation ...

    let cache_key = make_cache_key(&auth.tenant_id, &dto);

    // Attempt cache hit
    if let Ok(cached) = redis_conn.get::<_, Vec<u8>>(cache_key.clone()).await {
        if !cached.is_empty() {
            debug!("cache hit");
            let value: Paginated<LedgerEntry> = serde_json::from_slice(&cached)?;
            return Ok(Json(value));
        }
    }

    // Cache miss – fetching from service layer
    let result = state.query_service.query_entries(filter, pagination).await?;

    // Store in cache – set TTL 60s
    let ttl_seconds = 60;
    if let Ok(serialized) = serde_json::to_vec(&result) {
        let _: () = redis_conn.set_ex(cache_key, serialized, ttl_seconds).await?;
    }

    Ok(Json(result))
}
```

